To clean up that hedge, the [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) might use cash. Denote the. amount held in cash by. $M$ , so that the fund's remaining funds,. $\$140-M$ are invested in the 20-year bond. Then, as mentioned in Section 4.4, the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of this [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) is the weighted average of its component durations. Note, too, that the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of cash equals zero: its present value always equals its amount, no matter how rates change. Therefore, setting the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of this [asset portfolio](.md) equal to the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities,.  
$$
{\frac{M}{140}}\times0+{\frac{140-M}{140}}\times15.56=16.66
$$  

Solving,e $M=-9.90$ , meaning that the [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) would borrow $\$9.90$ million, or about. $7\%$ of the. $\$140$ million, and invest $\$140-(-9.90)=$ $\$149.90$ or about $107\%$ in the 20-year bond.  

The [asset portfolio](.md) just described hedges the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) risk of the liabilities. But how does the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the [asset portfolio](.md) compare with the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the liabilities? As mentioned in Section 4.5, the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of a [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) is the weighted average of the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of its components. Here, with the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of cash equal to zero and the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the 20-year bond equal to 141.49, the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the [asset portfolio](.md) is,  
$$
{\frac{-9.90}{140}}\times0+{\frac{149.90}{140}}\times141.49=151.50
$$  

which is less than the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the liabilities, given earlier as 211.37. Hence, this [asset portfolio](.md) results in the [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) having an overall negatively convex position. Figure 4.11 graphs the. $\mathrm{P}\&\mathrm{L}$ of this [asset portfolio](.md) and of the liabilities, where the P&L of the bond is calculated as a shift in its yield, and the. $\mathrm{P}\&\mathrm{L}$ of the liabilities by parallel shifts in the HQM par. rate curve. As rates fall, the values of both the liabilities and the asset port-. folio increase, as envisioned by the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) hedge. Because of the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md). hedge, in fact, the values of both increase by about the same amount for rela-. tively small [rate changes](../Chapter%207/Profit%20and%20Loss%20Attribution%20with%20an%20OAS.md). But because the liabilities have a higher [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md),. the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities increases more as rates decline. Therefore, for large declines in rates, the increase in value of the liabilities is greater than the increase in value of the assets, which leaves the [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) with a net loss in value.  

![](809c36d3a9e5895f6443c63c7e2182a308fe4cc83550bfdefa479e77d02b66f0.jpg)  
FIGURE 4.11 $\mathrm{P}\&\mathrm{L}$ of the [Pension Fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) Liabilities in Figure 4.10 and of a [Portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) Borrowing $\$9.90$ Million and Investing $\$149.90$ Million in the Johnson $\&$ Johnson 2.10s of 09/1/2040. The $\mathrm{P}\&\mathrm{L}$ of the Liabilities Is Computed Under a Parallel Shift of HQM Par Rates. The P&L of the Bond Is Computed by a Shift in Its Yield.  

As rates increase, the values of both the liabilities and the [asset portfolio](.md). fall, again as envisioned by the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) hedge. But because the liabilities. have a higher [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md), the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities falls more as rates. increase. Therefore, for large increases in rates, [the fall](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Articles/The%20Fall%20of%20Bear%20Stearns%20Lost%20Opportunities%20Haunt%20Final%20Days%20of%20Bear%20Stearns;%20Executives%20Bickeredover%20Raising%20Cash%20Cutting%20Mortgages.md) in the value of the liabilities is less than [the fall](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Articles/The%20Fall%20of%20Bear%20Stearns%20Lost%20Opportunities%20Haunt%20Final%20Days%20of%20Bear%20Stearns;%20Executives%20Bickeredover%20Raising%20Cash%20Cutting%20Mortgages.md) in value of the assets, which, again, leaves the. [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) with a net loss in value..  

The [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) could manage this [negative convexity](../Chapter%2015/Mortgage%20Pricing%20Spreads%20and%20Duration.md) by adjusting its hedge as rates change. As rates fall, and the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities increases more than the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the assets, the fund could increase its asset [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) by borrowing more cash and buying more bonds. As rates rise, and the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities falls more than that of the assets, the fund could lower its asset [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) by selling bonds and paying off some of its borrowing. This solution is fine in theory and sometimes in practice, but it is costly in the sense of requiring potentially frequent [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) rebalancing.  

Another approach is to find an [asset portfolio](.md) that not only matches the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities, but that also has a [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) equal to or greater. than that of the liabilities. There are, of course, many such portfolios that. can be formed from cash and the JNJ bonds listed in Table 4.6. For discussion purposes, Table 4.7 lists the [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) already discussed, along with two additional, two-asset portfolios.  

