The first row of the table corresponds to the [asset portfolio](.md) already analyzed. Its [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) equals 16.66, which equals the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities, but its [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) is significantly less than 211, the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the liabilities. The second row gives a [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) invested in the five-year and 30-year bonds,. with the proportions such that the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the [asset portfolio](.md) matches that of the liabilities. The [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) is 205.47, which is quite close to the 211.37 [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the liabilities. The third row gives an asset. [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) that once again matches the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md), this time by investing much more in cash and the residual in the 40-year bond. This [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) has a [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of 271.84, which exceeds that of the liabilities.  

The relative convexities of the asset portfolios in Table 4.7 illustrate the following general principle: among portfolios with the same [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md), the more spread out the cash flows of a [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md), the greater its [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md). All portfolios in the table are constructed to have the same [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md), but the first [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) is essentially all in the 20-year bond. In the [asset-liability management](../../Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md) context, this [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) is called a bullet [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md): the liability. cash flows, which are spread over many years, are being hedged by a single bond with matching [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md). The second [asset portfolio](.md) in the table is split. between five-year and 30-year bonds, while the third is split between cash -- essentially a zero-year bond - and 40-year bonds. These two [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) are. called barbell portfolios, because they are [hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) liabilities using one bond. with less [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) than the liabilities and one bond with more.  

Matched-[duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) portfolios with cash flows that are more spread out have greater convexities because, as explained earlier, [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) is roughly linear in term, while [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) is quadratic. Consider a 10-year zero coupon bond at a yield of zero, which, according to Equations (4.28) and (4.33), has a [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of 10 and a [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of. $10\times10.5=105$ . By contrast, a [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) with $50\%$ of its value in a five-year zero coupon bond and $50\%$ in a 15-year zero, using the same equations, also has a [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) 10, but a [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of $50\%$ times the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the five-year zero, 22.5, plus $50\%$ times the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the 15-year zero, 232.5, which equals 127.5. Because [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) is quadratic in term, the [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) of the 15-year zero dominates. Hence, the [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) with the more spread-out cash flows - the one with the longest-term bond - has the greatest [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md).  

Given the calculations in Table 4.7, how should the [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) choose. among the alternatives? Figure 4.12 graphs the net P&L of the liabilities and each of the asset portfolios. The net. $\mathrm{P}\&\mathrm{L}$ of the liabilities and the bullet [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md), $-7\%$ in cash and $107\%$ in the 20-year bond, is clearly negatively. convex: it loses value whether rates fall or rise. The barbell [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) with. $25\%$ in the five-year bond and $75\%$ in the 30-year bond, which matches the. [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) and approximately matches the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of the liabilities, gives rise. to a net $\mathrm{P}\&\mathrm{L}$ that is very small over a wide range of rates. In other words, a [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) with this [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) need not rebalance its [asset portfolio](.md) unless. rates fall significantly. Lastly, the barbell [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) with $31\%$ in cash and $69\%$ in the 40-year, gives rise to an overall, positively convex position. The combination of assets and liabilities gains value whether rates fall or rise.  

