Does Figure 4.12 prove that the [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) should always choose the most convex [asset portfolio](.md)? The answer is no. As mentioned in Section 4.6, evaluating P&L purely as a function of [changes in rates](../Chapter%203/Pl%20Attribution.md) does not account for the passage of time. As a rough proxy for return as time passes with rates unchanged, consider the weighted-average yields in Table 4.7, which fall with [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md). In other words, markets recognize the contribution of [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) to $\mathrm{P}\&\mathrm{L}$ as rates change, as shown in Figure 4.12, and, therefore, offer. lower yields for highly convex portfolios. As a result, a [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) with relatively low [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) and relatively high yield underperforms if rates change a lot but outperforms if rates stay about the same. By contrast, a [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md). with relatively high [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) and relatively low yield outperforms if rates change a lot but underperforms if rates stay about the same..  

Figure 4.13 illustrates the trade-off between yield and [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) by graphing the yields of the JNJ bonds from Table 4.6 against their durations. The curve has a concave shape, meaning that any line connecting two points on the curve is below the curve. Now, in the context of this graph, compare the second [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) from Table 4.7 - the barbell of the five-year and 30-year bonds - versus the bullet 20-year bond [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md). The barbell [portfolio](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md), with a [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of 16.66 and a weighted-average yield of. $2.32\%$ corresponds to the point on the dotted line at a [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of 16.66. By the concavity of the yield-[duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) curve, this yield is very much below the yield of the 20-year bond, which has a similar [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md).4 More generally, the concavity of the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md)-yield curve implies that the weighted-average yield on portfolios with more spread-out component bonds, which are more convex portfolios, is lower than the yield of bullet portfolios and also of less spread-out - less convex - portfolios. Chapter 8 demonstrates more formally how the shape of the [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) ensures that the benefits of [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) are fairly offset by lower return.  

