Given the discussion in the last several paragraphs, a [pension fund](../Chapter%2013/Uses%20of%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) man-. ager who decides to match the [duration](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) of assets and liabilities has to decide whether to trade yield for [positive convexity](Convexity.md). An [asset portfolio](.md) with a rela-. tively low yield but [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) exceeding that of the liabilities does not have. to be rebalanced often to avoid losses, does relatively well when rates move a lot, and does relatively poorly when rates do not move much. An asset port-. folio with a relatively high yield but [convexity](../../../Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing/Problem%20Sets/PSET%20II%20Fixed%20Income%20Asset%20Pricing%201.md) less than that of the liabilities has to be rebalanced often to avoid losses, does relatively poorly when rates move a lot, and does relatively well when rates do not move much. To summarize, then, the choice actually depends on whether rates will change by much or not, that is, on [future interest rate](../../../Clippings/Forward%20Rate.md) volatility!.  

# Key-Rate, Partial, and Forward-Bucket '01s and Durations  

The assumption in Chapter 4 that changes in the entire [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) can be described by one interest rate factor may be convenient and appropriate in certain situations, but applications with exposures across the [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) require more realistic foundations. Consider a life insurance com-. pany that has liabilities spread out over many years in the future. The insurer could make assumptions about how rates across the [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) typically vary with the 10-year [par rate](../Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) and then hedge all of its liabilities by buying 10-year bonds. But what if, over a particular period, the 30-year rate falls and the 10-year rate stays the same? The present value of liabilities would. increase, asset value would be unchanged, and the insurer would experience a net loss in value.  

Given that a one-factor framework cannot reliably describe [rate changes](../Chapter%207/Profit%20and%20Loss%20Attribution%20with%20an%20OAS.md). across the [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md), market participants have pursued three broad strategies. First, build a multi-factor [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) model, based on a combination of data and [market analysis](../../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/II.%20The%20Roles%20of%20Banks%20and%20Derivative%20Markets%20in%20Resolving%20Problems%20Inherent%20in%20Debt%20Contracts/Class%203-%20Financial%20Intermediation%20and%20Delegated%20Loan%20Monitoring%20,%20Intro%20to%20Bankruptcy%20and%20Debt%20Restructuring/Gordon%20Bargain%20Stores%20B.md). Many active [hedge funds](../../../Financial%20Engineering/Basis%20Trade%20Explainer.md) and asset managers, who build such models for [investment](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) purposes anyway, pursue. this path for [hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) as well. The Gauss+ model presented in Chapter 9 is an example of this approach. Second, hedge based on empirical analyses of. relationships across rates of various terms. Examples of this approach are given in Chapter 6. Third, adopt a robust approach to [hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md), which per-. forms well regardless of how the [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) evolves but which leaves little room for subjective views and gives no guidance as to [investment](../../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) deci-. sions. Many asset-liability managers and market makers, who do not see. themselves in the business of taking views on [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) movements, pursue this path, which is the subject of this chapter..  

The extreme of robust approaches to [hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) is immunization, that is,.   
[hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) away the risk of every single [cash flow](../../Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Preview%20of%20the%20Book.md). An example would be buying.   
eight zero coupon bonds to fund eight semesters of college tuition payments.  

No matter what happens to [interest rates](../Chapter%202/Interest%20Rate%20Quotations.md) and the [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md), the maturing zero coupon bonds will fund the assumed payments. Immunization is not practical, however, in many institutional contexts. An insurance company has too many liabilities on too many future dates for each of them to be funded - and therefore hedged - individually. Aside from the operational costs of such a program, the transaction costs of buying relatively small quantities of so many different [fixed income securities](../../../Clippings/Bond%20Equivalent%20Yield%20(BEY)%20-%20Definition,%20Formula,%20and%20Example.md) is likely to be prohibitive.  

Practical approaches to robust [hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md), therefore, incorporate enough factors to ensure acceptable performance under a wide range of [term structure](../Chapter%209/The%20Vasicek%20Model.md) scenarios but limit the number of factors to maintain tractability and contain transaction costs. The three approaches described in this. chapter - key-rate $^{\ '}O1s$ and durations, partial. $^{\mathrm{~,~}01s\mathrm{~-~}}$ and [forward-bucket](../Chapter%205/Forward-Bucketo1s.md) $^{\ '}01s$ , have proved popular as striking a sensible balance between [hedging](../Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md). effectiveness and practicality or cost. The final section of the chapter briefly. connects [multi-factor exposures](../Chapter%205/Multi-Factor%20Exposures%20and%20Portfolio%20Volatility.md) with [portfolio volatility](../../../Financial%20Engineering/2.%20Forwards,%20Swaps,%20Futures,%20and%20Options.md)..  